# Git Bash & Linux Essential Commands

## Git Bash Commands
git init         → Initialize a new Git repository
git status       → Show current repo status
git add <file>   → Stage file for commit
git commit -m "" → Commit staged files with message
git log          → Show commit history
git branch       → List/create branches
git checkout <branch> → Switch branch
git checkout -b <branch> → Create & switch branch
git merge <branch> → Merge a branch into current branch
git pull         → Fetch & merge from remote
git fetch        → Fetch updates from remote
git push         → Push commits to remote
git clone <url>  → Copy repo from remote
git remote -v    → Show remote URLs
git diff         → Show changes
git reset <file> → Unstage file

## Linux / Git Bash Core Commands
ls               → List files & directories
cd <dir>         → Change directory
pwd              → Show current directory path
mkdir <dir>      → Create a new directory
touch <file>     → Create a new empty file
rm <file>        → Remove a file
rm -r <dir>      → Remove directory recursively
cp <source> <dest> → Copy file/directory
mv <source> <dest> → Move or rename file/directory
cat <file>       → View file content
nano <file>      → Edit file in terminal
echo "text" > file → Write text to file
grep "text" <file> → Search text in file
chmod <mode> <file> → Change file permissions
chown <user> <file> → Change file owner
history          → Show command history
clear            → Clear terminal screen

# Tip: Practice these commands daily to become confident in Git Bash & Linux
